1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,411
Take time out to confer with yourself and tap your supreme thinking power.

2
00:00:06,641 --> 00:00:11,570
We usually picture leaders as exceptionally busy people, and they are.

3
00:00:11,920 --> 00:00:17,090
Leadership requires being in the thick of things, but while it's usually overlooked,

4
00:00:17,121 --> 00:00:25,010
it is noteworthy that leaders spend considerable time alone, alone with nothing but their own thinking apparatus.

5
00:00:25,520 --> 00:00:32,050
Check the lives of the great religious leaders, and you'll find each of them spent considerable time alone.

6
00:00:32,480 --> 00:00:36,691
Moses frequently was alone, often for long periods of time.

7
00:00:36,960 --> 00:00:41,171
So were Jesus, Buddha, Confucius, Muhammad, Gandhi.

8
00:00:41,280 --> 00:00:48,931
Every outstanding religious leader in history spent much time in solitude, away from the distractions of life.

9
00:00:49,760 --> 00:00:57,411
Political leaders, too, those who made lasting names in history, for good or bad, gained insight through solitude.

10
00:00:57,760 --> 00:01:09,490
It is an interesting question whether Franklin D. Roosevelt could have developed his unusual leadership capacities had he not spent much time alone while recovering from his polio attack.

11
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:16,291
Harry Truman spent much time as a boy and as an adult alone on a Missouri farm.

12
00:01:16,880 --> 00:01:26,291
Quite possibly, Hitler would never have achieved power had he not spent months in jail alone where he had time to construct Mein Kampf,

13
00:01:26,480 --> 00:01:32,530
that brilliantly wicked plan for world conquest that sold the Germans in a blind moment.

14
00:01:33,201 --> 00:01:38,130
Many of the leaders of communism who proved to be so diplomatically skillful,

15
00:01:38,240 --> 00:01:43,650
Lenin, Stalin, Marx, and many others, spent time in jail where they could,

16
00:01:43,681 --> 00:01:46,851
without distraction, plan their future moves.

17
00:01:47,600 --> 00:01:53,331
Leading universities require professors to lecture as few as five hours per week,

18
00:01:53,360 --> 00:01:55,971
so that the professor has time to think.

19
00:01:56,960 --> 00:02:05,090
Many outstanding business executives are surrounded all day by assistants, secretaries, telephones and reports.

20
00:02:05,360 --> 00:02:11,090
But follow them around for 168 hours a week and 720 hours a month,

21
00:02:11,280 --> 00:02:16,451
and you discover they spent a surprising amount of time in uninterrupted thought.

22
00:02:17,040 --> 00:02:18,371
The point is this.

23
00:02:18,641 --> 00:02:24,931
The successful person in any field takes time out to confer with himself or herself.

24
00:02:25,360 --> 00:02:30,771
Leaders use solitude to put the pieces of a problem together, to work out solutions,

25
00:02:30,880 --> 00:02:35,251
to plan, and in one phrase, to do their super-thinking.

26
00:02:36,480 --> 00:02:44,931
Many people fail to tap their creative leadership power because they confer with everybody and everything else but themselves.

27
00:02:45,280 --> 00:02:47,331
You know this kind of person well.

28
00:02:47,440 --> 00:02:51,090
He's the fellow who goes to great lengths not to be alone.

29
00:02:51,280 --> 00:02:54,851
He goes to extremes to surround himself with people.

30
00:02:55,040 --> 00:03:00,130
He can't stand being alone in his office, so he goes prowling to see other people.

31
00:03:00,400 --> 00:03:02,931
Seldom does he spend evenings alone.

32
00:03:03,201 --> 00:03:07,490
He feels a compelling need to talk with others every waking moment.

33
00:03:07,681 --> 00:03:11,570
He devours a huge diet of small talk and gossip.

34
00:03:12,480 --> 00:03:20,050
When this person is forced by circumstances to be physically alone, he finds ways to keep from being mentally alone.

35
00:03:20,320 --> 00:03:29,411
At times like these, he resorts to television, newspapers, radio, telephone, anything that will take over his thinking process for him.

36
00:03:29,760 --> 00:03:36,050
In effect, he says, Here, Mr. TV, Mr. Newspaper, occupy my mind for me.

37
00:03:36,239 --> 00:03:39,650
I am afraid to occupy it with my own thoughts.

38
00:03:40,880 --> 00:03:45,411
Mr. I-Can't-Stand-To-Be-Alone shuns independent thought.

39
00:03:45,520 --> 00:03:47,971
He keeps his own mind blacked out.

40
00:03:48,080 --> 00:03:51,411
He is psychologically scared of his own thoughts.

41
00:03:51,681 --> 00:03:57,251
As time goes by, Mr. I-Can't-Stand-To-Be-Alone grows increasingly shallow.

42
00:03:57,360 --> 00:03:59,971
He makes many ill-considered moves.

43
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:04,851
He fails to develop firmness of purpose, personal stability.

44
00:04:05,201 --> 00:04:11,731
He is unfortunately ignorant of the superpower lying unused just behind his forehead.

45
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:15,891
Don't be a Mr. I-can't-stand-to-be-alone.

46
00:04:16,080 --> 00:04:19,891
Successful leaders tap their superpower through being alone.

47
00:04:20,080 --> 00:04:21,251
You can too.

48
00:04:21,520 --> 00:04:23,121
Let's see how.
